<subSubSection id="C3776556EFEF3A8BFF78F8BAFC4AFEEC" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEFEF3A8BFF78F8BAFC4AFEEC" blockId="190.[136,778,1771,2070]" lastBlockId="190.[810,1452,173,301]" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEFEF3A8BFF78F8BAFEEFF84F" bold="true" box="[189,298,1908,1934]" pageId="190" pageNumber="191">Remarks</emphasis>
. This genus has remained monotypic since itsdiscovery.Inhisoriginaldiagnosisof thegenus 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEFEF3A8BFD6CF858FF16F813" author="Monniot, C." journalOrPublisher="Cahiers de Biologie Marine" pageId="190" pageNumber="191" pagination="459 - 467" part="24" refId="ref329974" refString="Monniot, C. (1983) Microra angulata n. g., n. sp. et Remex obesus n. g., n. sp., copepodes parasites d'une ascidie de Guadeloupe. Cahiers de Biologie Marine, 24, 459 - 467. https: // doi. org / 10.21411 / CBM. A. 607 E 6 AE 2" title="Microra angulata n. g., n. sp. et Remex obesus n. g., n. sp., copepodes parasites d'une ascidie de Guadeloupe" type="journal article" year="1983">Monniot (1983)</bibRefCitation>
highlighted the reduced size of leg 1, the presence of a single exopodal seta on the 3-segmented antenna, the 1-segmented endopods of legs 1 to 4, and the presence of 2 claws on the caudal rami. Here we confirm that the endopods are actually 2-segmented, each comprising a small unarmed proximal segment and a setiferous second segment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
